M|rules|title: Early Length Check for Array Comparisons
M|rules|impact: MEDIUM-HIGH
M|rules|impactDescription: avoids expensive operations when lengths differ
M|rules|tags: javascript, arrays, performance, optimization, comparison
M|rules|When comparing arrays with expensive operations (sorting, deep equality, serialization), check lengths first. If lengths differ, the arrays cannot be equal.
M|rules|In real-world applications, this optimization is especially valuable when the comparison runs in hot paths (event handlers, render loops).
M|rules|**Incorrect (always runs expensive comparison):**
M|rules|```typescript
M|rules|function hasChanges(current: string[], original: string[]) {
M|rules|// Always sorts and joins, even when lengths differ
M|rules|return current.sort().join() !== original.sort().join()
M|rules|}
M|rules|```
M|rules|Two O(n log n) sorts run even when `current.length` is 5 and `original.length` is 100. There is also overhead of joining the arrays and comparing the strings.
M|rules|**Correct (O(1) length check first):**
M|rules|```typescript
M|rules|function hasChanges(current: string[], original: string[]) {
M|rules|// Early return if lengths differ
M|rules|if (current.length !== original.length) {
M|rules|return true
M|rules|}
M|rules|// Only sort when lengths match
M|rules|const currentSorted = current.toSorted()
M|rules|const originalSorted = original.toSorted()
M|rules|for (let i = 0; i < currentSorted.length; i++) {
M|rules|if (currentSorted[i] !== originalSorted[i]) {
M|rules|return true
M|rules|}
M|rules|}
M|rules|return false
M|rules|}
M|rules|```
M|rules|This new approach is more efficient because:
M|rules|- It avoids the overhead of sorting and joining the arrays when lengths differ
M|rules|- It avoids consuming mem for the joined strings (especially important for large arrays)
M|rules|- It avoids mutating the original arrays
M|rules|- It returns early when a difference is found